<review>I'm not one to go out of my way to write up complaints unless needed, but this calls for it.

1) Cost
From day 1, the manager, Jim, told us they are 30% cheaper than the dealership price with a free evaluation. We were very pleased with the things he had to say on the phone, so we decided to go ahead and have them work on my car. After they diagnosed it, found out it was an $800 charge, whereas Ford's price was $125. The price we got from Ford was about $4,000 for a new transmission including labor and all. Jim told us it would be between $1500-$2500. Later in the week, he changed his answer to $3800 for the final price. I couldn't take it to Ford where I would've rather taken it back to because I was apparently down $800 regardless, so we stayed with not much of a choice.

2) Rental/charge
The first thing he told us was the rentals were free. Another time, told us only the $25 rental was free (a Fiat). We had the "upgraded" car that was $40 so he said he'd take off $25 off each day. Great! When I was picking up my car, I found out he had tacked on all the charges on top of the original price he gave us. The whole cost of this entire thing was about $4500. The "discounted" price should have been off the $3800 total that he gave us. He failed to provide us with those details. Not only was that inching toward one grand more than his original price, his quote of "30% cheaper than the dealership price" was invalid.

3) Timeframe/duration
Day one, he told us it would be 3-5 days until I have my car back. We had it towed over there on Tuesday and told us they would call us Friday and again, changed his answer to 5-7 days. That following Monday, he calls and tells us that they barely took it apart and gave us the cost. He then told us it should be ready Wednesday. Wednesday comes and they test drove it and it jolted when changing gears so they had to work on it and would be ready Thursday. Thursday comes, nothing. Finally got my car back today (Saturday) with no communication in between.

Overall, we will not be doing business with them again. We don't work with shady liars and will be contacting the headquarters about all of this. The lack of communication is very unprofessional. 1446327183133< /date>
<Rating>1< /Rating>< review>
I'm not one to go out of my way to write up complaints unless needed, but this calls for it.

1) Cost
From day 1, the manager, Jim, told us they are 30% cheaper than the dealership price with a free evaluation. We were very pleased with the things he had to say on the phone, so we decided to go ahead and have them work on my car. After they diagnosed it, found out it was an $800 charge, whereas Ford's price was $125. The price we got from Ford was about $4,000 for a new transmission including labor and all. Jim told us it would be between $1500-$2500. Later in the week, he changed his answer to $3800 for the final price. I couldn't take it to Ford where I would've rather taken it back to because I was apparently down $800 regardless, so we stayed with not much of a choice.

2) Rental/charge
The first thing he told us was the rentals were free. Another time, told us only the $25 rental was free (a Fiat). We had the "upgraded" car that was $40 so he said he'd take off $25 off each day. Great! When I was picking up my car, I found out he had tacked on all the charges on top of the original price he gave us. The whole cost of this entire thing was about $4500. The "discounted" price should have been off the $3800 total that he gave us. He failed to provide us with those details. Not only was that inching toward one grand more than his original price, his quote of "30% cheaper than the dealership price" was invalid.

3) Timeframe/duration
Day one, he told us it would be 3-5 days until I have my car back. We had it towed over there on Tuesday and told us they would call us Friday and again, changed his answer to 5-7 days. That following Monday, he calls and tells us that they barely took it apart and gave us the cost. He then told us it should be ready Wednesday. Wednesday comes and they test drove it and it jolted when changing gears so they had to work on it and would be ready Thursday. Thursday comes, nothing. Finally got my car back today (Saturday) with no communication in between.

Overall, we will not be doing business with them again. We don't work with shady liars and will be contacting the headquarters about all of this. The lack of communication is very unprofessional. The fact that he tacked on money we weren't aware of is very unprofessional. We were taken advantage of and it ruined the entire company for us. I hope you're proud, Jim.</review>

<Name>Ivars Bezdechi< /Name><time>1399056419427</time><Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
Bright Now Dental's "$29 Cleaning and Exam" is a bait-and-switch thing. They get you in the door, do the x-rays, and most conveniently later on telling you that you need a $79 procedure (and after the other expenses you will be leaving spending $100) explaining that the "cleaning" is actually just a "polishing" which will push buildup back into your gums.   Dr. Pham (I'm not sure that is his name) seemed to know what he is doing when he examined the x-rays and probed around.  I didn't like that between the hygienist and the doctor coming into the room you just sat there staring at a wall for long periods of time.  Bright Now comes off as the Walmartization of dental care, and I would much rather deal with a traditional dentist who hasn't signed up for a franchise.  The office was clean, equipment very high tech.  But the bait-and-switch tactic, the long waits between being seated in the chair, waiting for the hygienist to come in, and the long wait for the dentist to come in, and another long wait for the head receptionist to come in to do a sales pitch for all of the recommended work left a really bad impression on me.  Well, at least for $10 bucks (for the x-rays) I found out that my teeth are in relatively good shape.</Review>

When i asked about it, i was offered a card with the 2 bowls i was purchasing checked off and 1 Extra check mark...

Really?
1 extra...?

You alone have sold me at least a dozen bowls RECENTLY and there are no other employees :-/

I was just being lazy not making my own.

If I'm desperate, i'll be back.

But i'll just be making my own.

Here's how:
They use the exactly same tasting/textured Organic Acai as costco sells.
1) Go buy a 1/2 gallon tub there. No costco membership? Don't be a moron... you'll make the money from the annual fee back in 1 purchase of camping gear,  booze, carne asada, toilet paper or 10 million other products that all have a 100% lifetime refund guarantee!
2) get fresh LOCAL fruit every sunday at the Hillcrest farmers market... trust me, this is the best market for local organic fruit! Orrrr buy super cheap organic fresh or frozen fruit at costco!
3) while at costco,  get organic peanut butter, organic hemp seeds, organic mixed granola cereal (10Xs better than Juice Wave granola IMO and organic honey if you're into it.)

Make your sh at home...its fast,  easy and wayyyyy cheaper,  like 100Xs cheaper (that is not hyperbole) and custom make your acai bowl to perfection.

Good product nice people but no loyalty... lame.<//review>

I went for a weekly rental on a hybrid. The bike I received was patently unsafe and in terrible condition. The rear wheel was severely warped. The tires were underinflated. Both brakes were so soft that stopping quickly was impossible (the warped rear wheel makes functioning brakes impossible). The derailleur was not functioning properly, gears did not stay in place and would rattle loudly. The entire drive train looked like it hadn't been lubricated in a year.
This was the only hybrid they had in my size, so I went and found a much better hybrid at another shop for only a few extra dollars. I returned the bike after a few hours on the first day. Out of a $72 rental, I received only a $33 refund. I wouldn't mind a nominal fee, but charging me nearly $40 for an unsafe bike is terrible business practice.<//text>

< Review>
Located in the heart of Solvang, the Hamlet Inn made our stay there even more enjoyable. The hotel is very clean and very nicely decorated. We stayed in the Queen suite and there was a little nook facing the window so we were able to people watch while we enjoyed our delicious danishes we grabbed from right across the street. The room has air conditioning and a flat screen tv. There was even a couch in the room and it was by no means crowded. The property was private and quiet but we were still able to make some late night trips to the casino, which was 5 minutes away. I love Solvang and I had originally chosen The Hamlet Inn because the price was extremely reasonable, but now, having stayed there for 3 nights, I would gladly return and pay top dollar. Great experience üëç</Review>

Andrea Schoeny<//user_name>
<date>1520224387103<//date><Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
The front desk is very helpful. We were given good recommendations that fit our budget and vacation style (museums and food). Clean, simple room. The long desk running under the window is a nice touch. Good natural light. Comfy beds and plenty of pillows and blankets. Bathroom could use more counter space and the shower/toilet room was cold. Two for one wine tasting coupon provided was a nice touch, in addition to breakfast coupon for Olsen's Bakery. Overall, kind of expensive, but considering the area, was a deal. We would stay at Hamlet Inn again.</Review>

<user>105092658195117649597< /user><user_name>Jen H<//user_name><date>1423250661343</date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
< Review>
- Room 9 Review -

A convenient motel that's modernized with Danish furnishing in the heart of Solvang. Hamlet Inn is a great selection; there's two happening bars across the Street for the night and Paula's Pancake for the morning.,,there's not much night activities here, so being across the street from a bar (Viking Bar on Fridays) with live entertainment was a bonus!

As for the room itself, the place is clean and simple. The room has the essentials: 2 sets of towel, soaps, shampoo, blow dryer, cups, tissues, ice bucket, and a comfy bed with three pillows. I'm not sure if Hamlet has a toothbrush/toothpaste set available, so bring your own or call ahead to ask. Hamlet Inn is not cheap due to the being in the heart of Solvang, but you pay for the convenience if that's what you're looking for.

Checkout is at 11am and check in is at 1pm; Free bike rentals can be returned by 1pm if you're checking out that same day. PS. Hamlet offers some 2 for 1 coupons for wine tastings, so make sure to ask!<//Review>

<Text>For more almost $250 a night after taxes, this place doesn't give you much. Yes, it's quaint. Yes they've put some effort into updating the rooms. But:

The pillows are those flat, hard, crap pillows that you find at your bargain $39.99 roadside inn. Seriously, the worst pillows imaginable.

The bed was so-so and the AC seemed to really struggle to keep the room cool.

Fortunately, they're smack dab in the middle of a Solvang so they don't have to work too hard.

<Rating>3</Rating>< review>
As a preface to my comments below, I'd like to say I've been going to this restaurant every year for the last 15 years in both the winter and summer months.  I've never had a problem with the food or service as we've always had a good experience. This year, we visited again, and because of COVID-19 restrictions we were forced to eat outdoors.  We were immediately seated at a table that was slanted so no matter where you sat the you would have to be very careful how you put things down or else risk them sliding off. It made me feel uneasy.   I asked if we could be moved to another "flat" table but the owner mentioned everything was booked, even though there were other similarly sized tables completely open.  When I mentioned moving again, the owner suggested   leveling the table with rocks and said I was the only visitor that had complained about the table.  So given that logic, why couldn't you simply offer us another table seeing as how someone else wouldn't mind ours?  I brought this up and the owner threw the rocks he had been holding to the ground and stormed off, never to be heard from again.  I can't believe we were treated like that without making even an ounce to accommodate us.  Needless to say, this whole experience ruined our dinner and we chose instead to get our food to go.</review>

<UserId.>112006624500941097579</UserId.><Name>Scott Dukes</Name>< Time>
1534110052164< /Time>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< Text>
Our favorite meal during a weeklong stay in Lake Tahoe. Restaurant is in a converted, authentic log cabin. The interior is adorable, but it is also quite a small space. You will need to call a day or two ahead for reservations for a weeknight dinner, or even further ahead for a weekend dinner.

Service was fantastic, and the food was even better. Come hungry! Entrees come with soup and a starch, and homemade bread and butter comes out at the start of the meal.

We ordered a variety of dishes, all great but the seafood stood out. The scallops in my pasta dish were some of the best I've ever had. They have a different homemade ice cream each day. Ours was an almond cinnamon ice cream and I am still thinking about it!

Don't miss out on Soule Domain.< /Text>
< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNhfWrmMoQQqXKlY0RSxHFto0PHnW2_tQB9rDrb=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>
<Response>None</Response>< gmapID>

<user_id>101352509617013031863<//user_id><username>Andrew Ring</username>< Time>
1581754637642< /Time>
< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
Soule Domain managed to balance gourmet food with a relaxed, down to earth atmosphere. Located in a beautiful, yet cozy, log cabin situated on the California side of the Nevada border, it's something of a hidden treasure.

Our server, Steve, was a character in the best sense of the word. He was extremely knowledge about all of the dishes, and very friendly. He was unusually supportive in helping my wife find options she was happy with that worked with her dietary restrictions.

Every course was noteworthy. To begin with, there was a perfectly seasoned hummus with bread (he brought some fresh veggies for my wife, who is gluten free). There was an Asian salad which was fresh and perfectly sized to share. Soup was a carrot ginger, and was creamy whilst remaining vegan. My wife enjoyed a mustard chicken, while I had an Asian style Ono. Both were extremely good. To cap things off, I had a wonderful bread pudding, while my wife enjoyed fresh berries.

We will definitely return when in the area again.< /Text>

On a whim we decided to try Soule Domain for a nice evening out and it exceed our expectations. Steven was our server and he was incredible, so passionate and knowledgeable. He and the hostess (we didn't catch her name) were on top of it- it made the whole dinner very special and intimate. <pictures>None</pictures>< text>
My review is based on communication with staff at Soule Domain. I confirmed a reservation well in advance for tonight, Friday, at 8:15. I heard positive things about the restaurant overall and it was also endorsed by my property manager. Unfortunately, this sea-level accustomed traveler succumbed to altitude sickness, so I called to see if I could transfer my res. The first time I called, I was on hold for over ten minutes. I called back and explained that I was ill and asked if he could help me transfer my reservation to another time, perhaps the following night. I guess I expected a customer-servicey considerate response like "I'm sorry you're not feeling well, let me see what I do  about your reservation," but instead the man I spoke with was defensive and rude. He said "we're very busy and you have a large table, it would have to be 8:30" and then would not confirm the 8:30 availability (this time would have been fine with me). My reservation is for 4 people, so I think that will be helpful to future patrons who might have a group that exceeds Soule Domain's capability. I was really looking forward to celebrating my 30th birthday here with dear friends, and had I a choice in being ill vs. not-ill, I would have preferred the latter. The response I received from the staff at Soule Domain was rude, unprofessional, and ultimately unhelpful.
After a Google search, I found hundreds of results for restaurants in this area with excellent reviews and better hours of operation. I suggest looking to those first, as I am now doing, to hopefully have an enjoyable albeit belated birthday celebration.<//text>

<review>Great little place! Very small dining areas and the lower dining area was so so hot from the woodstove, almost too hot. But everything else was on point; appetizers, lamb ravioli (tasty) and sauteed Singapore shrimp (amazing!!), so delicious! The soup, well it was way too hot inside  to enjoy hot soup lol but it had a tomato flavor but potato soup consistency. My husband had the pork tenderloin, so tender, so flavorful. I had the filet mignon with the shitake and blue cheese, just fantastic and full of great,  savory flavor. The potatoes and veggies that accompanied the main course was perfectly cooked and seasoned. The service, impeccable, our main waiter was Wes he was super friendly, well informed and attentive. The other wait staff filled our waters, removed dishes and catered to our every need. <UserId.>116222037552217692719<//UserId.><rate>5< /rate>< text>
We've been here twice now, and to a point, I think the hype is worth it. The seafood (this time, a shrimp appetizer) is never overcooked and always fresh. Most dishes have some special reduction or sauce that is always very flavorful.

It's not a Michelen Star restaurant, and at times the portions are overwhelming, but given where you are (there's not much in the way of fine dining in Tahoe), it's really nice to have a place where you can get something that isn't a burger. And for $25-$35 a plate, it's a good deal.< /text>

< username>
Amy Liozza<//username>
<rating>3</rating>< Review>
We came mainly for the burgers so this review will basically be all about that. There is no shortage of parking in the back and we came on a Monday, so it might be different than on weekends. The vibes were akin to an Irish pub with some plush seats at the walls.

Our group basically decided to get 2 Bacon Bourbonators and 2 Morrison Filets. All came with fries and one of my friends decided to get truffle fries for a bit extra.

Fries were crisp, and the truffle fries were good. No issues there, and definitely felt good having those.

As for the burgers, I think they were good but not as crazy good as some people make it to believe. The meat was tender and juicy, but I didn't feel that it justifies the price personally. Still, it was a good burger with few issues.

The drinks were fine. There's a huge selection of drinks that I can appreciate and the all IPAs that I had here were good.

Overall, a good spot for friends and even some family as long as it's a weekday, and while the burger is good I dunno if it's justified for the price.< /Review>

<time>1596221470908<//time><rate>2<//rate>< Review>
Even before the pandemic, this place would not get the order correct about 50% of the time. My last visit took 2 trips through the drive through, I couldn't go inside to correct the order as they had locked the door due to guidelines, to get a correct order. There was no chance of a misunderstanding as I always ask them to repeat the order back, which he did. What I received however was 2 completely different meals with toppings I specifically asked to be removed. Second time around I received only 1 meal not the second.

This is a fairly busy McDonald's but that's no excuse for quality control. The other McDonalds in the area I've never received an incorrect order from. I won't be coming back to this one as I also get soggy greasy fries about 50% of the time on top of my order being wrong. Too much of a headache to deal with.<//Review>

< text>
I visited this location between 3-4am on my way home from work. Let's start off with the fact that the grill was being cleaned so they weren't serving burgers for the next 30 minutes or so. Normally this would affect my opinion in a negative manner but the way they handled the situation definitely deserves 5 stars.
I was only able to order chicken nuggets and fries but had originally come to pick up burgers. I'm not sure why but the drive thru line was taking forever so by the time I got to the window to pick up my food, it had been almost 20 minutes. I had asked the woman at the second window if the grill was back on yet since the guy that took my order said if I wanted burgers I'd have to wait 15-20 minutes. She apologized for the misinformation and informed me that it can actually take a little over 30 minutes. Making a long story shorter... This trip took me about 35 minutes but they did compensate me for the inconvenience and handled the situation in a friendly/professional manner.
This is also the only location, closest to Sherman Oaks, that is open 24-7.< /text>
